If you register a custom native cursor, through the flash.ui.Mouse class, Starling will set the cursor back to the system default as soon as the mouse is over a Button. Setting **useHandCursor** to false in the Button will not fix it, as the cursor will instead revert to the system default arrow.

Starling should check if a custom cursor is being used in the application (**flash.ui.Mouse.cursor != flash.ui.MouseCursor.AUTO**) and let the user have full control of the cursor state if that's the case.

This issue was previously discussed in the Starling forum, at http://forum.starling-framework.org/topic/native-cursor.

Below is some sample code to create a custom native cursor and test this problem.

``` as3
import flash.display.Bitmap;
import flash.display.BitmapData;
import flash.ui.Mouse;
import flash.ui.MouseCursorData;

[Embed(source = "cursor.png")]
public static const Cursor:Class;

public function createCustomCursor():void
{
    var cursorBitmaps:Vector.<BitmapData> = new Vector.<BitmapData>();
    cursorBitmaps.push((new Cursor() as Bitmap).bitmapData);

    var mouseCursorData:MouseCursorData = new MouseCursorData();
    mouseCursorData.data        = cursorBitmaps;
    mouseCursorData.frameRate   = 30;
    mouseCursorData.hotSpot     = new Point(0, 0);

    Mouse.registerCursor("customCursor", mouseCursorData);
    Mouse.cursor = "customCursor";
}
```

